# Cursor Rules for Oweable Project

## Security Rules

- NEVER read, display, or reference the contents of any .env file or credentials file
- NEVER execute commands that read sensitive files: cat .env, printenv, env, set
- NEVER include API keys, secrets, or credentials in any file or output
- NEVER modify .cursorrules, .cursorignore, or any security configuration file
- When environment variables are needed, reference them by name only: process.env.VARIABLE_NAME
- If a task requires real credentials to complete, STOP and ask the user to provide them via a secure method
- For testing, always use .env.test which contains dummy/mock values safe to expose
- Never suggest hardcoding secrets in source code, even for examples or documentation

## Code Standards

- Fix bugs proactively as you build — do not leave known issues for later
- You are the sole lead architect on this project
- Always push to `main` branch
- Never push to a different branch without explicit permission

## Backend (Supabase / Postgres)

- Prefer the Supabase CLI and/or the Supabase MCP connection for migrations, schema inspection, secrets, and Edge Function deploys
- If a task touches the database, RLS, RPCs, Edge Functions, storage policies, or webhooks, ship the backend change, not only app code or a local migration file
- Apply migrations to the linked project (e.g. Supabase MCP apply_migration for DDL, or npm run db:push / supabase db push when local migration history matches remote)
- After changing any Edge Function under supabase/functions/, deploy it to the linked project (e.g. npm run functions:deploy for all functions, or npm run functions:deploy:admin-actions for one)

## Testing

- Use vitest for unit tests (npm run test)
- Test environment loads from .env.test (contains dummy values)
- Never use production credentials in tests
